Description: Managing Kubernetes with all of its YAML files can be a pain, so this article will look at the tool Pepr to assist with that. First it talks a bit about the pieces around Pepr which seemed geared to Javascript programmers, which is fair enough. We get really started with the install and setup, which they refer to an external video. In our article, they compare Pepr to Kyverno and Operator frameworks. Next we take a peek into the architecture, and start with a huge diagram. They do point out the JS-like TypeScript is supposed to be plain english, and do illustrate that with a couple of examples. Next we talk about abstractions, and how there are three strong ones - modoule, capability and action, and we get another diagram to boot. They go through the dev loop, which I think is how all the actions are handled; we lost a bit of the plain english here. To follow that up, they mention that WebAssembly is also supported along with TS, and that it makes it more versatile and accessible. I think the access comes from languages that can compile to or output WebAssembly. Next we hop over to Logging and monitoring, and they talk about it for a few paras. We then are taken through Deployment, which shows us how it can be used in Prod, with another diagram. There are some more bits, including security and scaling that they talk about. It's an interesting tool, but there is some handwaving here and there and not a strong case made for why to jump to it, but it might be worth kicking the tires on.
BottomLine: New config-management tool Pepr for Kubernetes YAML
