URL reference: https://securityboulevard.com/2024/08/unraveling-the-state-of-kubernetes-security-in-2024/
DateReviewed: 2024-08-25
Description: This is a retrospective on RedHat's annual state of Kubernetes security for 2024, with various highlights pointed out. We dive in and start with misconfiguration, and while concern for this is decreasing, it's still an important concern as a misconfig can lead to a serious issue. Possible vulns ticks up as a concern, as more issues in the supply chain surface. Incidents have been dropping, but they are still over 2021 era levels. It seems DevSecOps is on the uptick, and means that orgs are taking security a bit more seriously. They include a handy chart with answers segmented over the last 4 years, highlighting things that are trending downward. The second part of this article is explaining how Armo addresses these issues, and it feels like an elaborate ad. I'm happy they talk to various points and highlight how their platform helps, but their conclusion that they cover "100% of the top risk concerns" doesn't ensure customers use the product correctly and mitigate those risks. I think it's fine to say your product mitigates or solves risks, but there is a lot of verbiage here at a high level. My overall take is the first part is helpful, and the pitch could have been a paragraph or two instead of being almost as long as the highlights.
BottomLine: First half is a strong summary of RedHat state of Kubernetes 2024 but second half is an odd ad
