URL reference: https://cloudbelievers.blogspot.com/2024/08/kubernetes-security-best-practices.html
DateReviewed: 2024-08-26
Description: Security is important in Kubernetes - and protecting service account tokens is an important component in this, which this article looks at. Account tokens is how apps communicate to the K8s API, but they argue that being too liberal with access can have bad consequences. To allow access to the token, K8s by default provides it with a mount into each pod. The arugement that they make is that rather than have a default permissive token, that each app should have a crafted token that only allows the permissions that are required. To control this, they recommend turning off the automatic mounting of the token store. They talk a bit about using RBAC to have the right permissions, along with audits and monitoring to track what is being done. Overall a decent piece.
BottomLine: Discussion and recommendations for security on Kubernetes service account tokens
