URL reference: https://itnext.io/kubernetes-manage-external-secrets-with-azure-workload-identity-11bc449c4935
DateReviewed: 2024-08-29
Description: This blog will use Workload identity with federated credentials to implement a zero trust approach. We start with a diagram, which is always a good sign. We start with Terraform to provision the environment, and we run through a config file and then init and create the plan, before applying and actually building the environment. They walk us through the built system in the Azure console, to show what has been created. We then go through a piece to set up the oidc (federation) provider, with a config and some outputs along with a CLI command. Next up, they use Helm to deploy an external secrets operator to enable your workload identity provider with two Helm CLI commands, and then another couple commands to create a namespace for the Identity provider and a template deployment to enable it. Another diagram or two, but they do go through the various parts in text to help us understand what is going on. Once that is done, they show us the YAML we need to use the external provider, and finally the kubectl CLI command to get it working. Another YAML file to inject secrets, and explaination of what is going on, an (optional) NS creation and finally applying it through kubectl CLI. They show us how to verify the provider is running and how to test for a secret to ensure it works.
BottomLine: Decent walkthrough of using federated identity on an Azure Kubernetes cluster
