URL reference: https://opensauced.pizza/blog/how-we-use-kubernetes-jobs-to-scale-openssf-scorecard
DateReviewed: 2024-08-30
Description: This is a discussion of how OpenSSF scorecard is run -- it itself is a way to assess the security of a workload running in a container. The focus of this article is the decisions made when building and running the project. We start with a bit of a rhetorical question - how do we get a cron-like behavior out of Kubernetes? They went with Kubernetes Jobs to achieve this functionality. Now they break down how this works, starting with a scheduler to run the jobs, run as a microservice. It's job is to start the K8s Jobs and then collect the results. They dive into the actual GO code, but what they are looking for is repos that have been updated and need testing. They deep dive into how the pool works and how many threads it can use. Once enoughh time passes, they have to update the scorecard for a repo, and schedule the check in K8s Jobs. It then waits for the completion for the results. They then travel through the various perms needed to run the jobs and for the K8s Jobs to have access to run those resources, as YAML. A great walk through!
BottomLine: Very solid walk through on using Kubernetes Jobs to run parts of the OpenSSF scorecard
